[Student "S"]
{With 12 points and an excellent suit you overcall 1\H.

Partner raises to 4\H and everyone passes.

South plays 4\H. West leads the \DA and the defense wins two high \Ds then switches to a trump.

<b>South plays 4\H. West leads the \DA and the defense wins two high \Ds then switches to a trump.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 0 : \D 2 : \C 2 : Total = 4

The two \D losers are already lost, so you must eliminate a \C loser. If West has the \CK then a simple finesse will win the day. That would be a 50% chance, right? <b>WRONG!</b> That would be a 0% chance. You and partner hold 23 HCP. West has already produced 4 HCP with the \DA, and if he had 3 more that would mean East opened with only 10 points. Very doubtful.

So face it, East has the \CK.

However, dummy has some nice \S cards. So you pull the last trump, play your \S3 to dummy's \SA, then lead the \SQ. If East puts on his \SK (which you know he must have) you ruff it. Then enter dummy with a \D ruff and discard the small \C on the good \SJ. If East doesn't play his \SK you discard your  \C loser immediately.

If you separate the bidding from the play in your mind you will too often miss clues that should be telling you that certain plans will or won't work.

This was a perfect example. After the opening lead it was easy to deduce that all the rest of the high cards had to be in the East hand.}
[Play "W"]DA

